id: claude-slash-command
title: Claude Code /tnl-feature skill installation
scope: feature
owners: [@jana]
paths: [src/commands/init.ts]
surfaces: [tnl init]
dependencies: [cli-init]

intent:
  When `tnl init` runs with the `--with-skill` opt-in flag AND Claude
  Code is a target agent, it writes `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md`
  as a thin pointer at the CLAUDE.md stanza, and the stanza appended
  to CLAUDE.md includes the `/tnl-feature` reference line. The skill
  is opt-in because CLAUDE.md's stanza already carries the full task
  flow; the skill adds only a discoverability breadcrumb for users
  who want an explicit slash command. Without `--with-skill`, neither
  the file nor the stanza line is written.

behaviors:
  - `src/commands/init.ts` MUST contain a fixed string constant `TNL_FEATURE_SKILL_TEMPLATE` whose body is the markdown content for `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md`. The content MUST be a thin pointer that (a) has YAML frontmatter with `description:`, (b) references `$ARGUMENTS`, (c) tells the agent to follow the TNL task flow defined in `CLAUDE.md` (the "TNL — Typed Natural Language" section) as authoritative, (d) does NOT duplicate the numbered task-flow steps. Single source of truth is the CLAUDE.md stanza; duplicating steps across stanza and skill creates drift and causes session-to-session variance depending on whether `/tnl-feature` was invoked.
  - When `tnl init` determines Claude is a target agent AND the `--with-skill` flag is set, init MUST write `<cwd>/.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` with `TNL_FEATURE_SKILL_TEMPLATE` content. It MUST create `.claude/commands/` if absent. When `--with-skill` is not set, the skill file MUST NOT be written, even when Claude is a target.
  - If `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` already exists under `--with-skill`, init MUST leave the file untouched and report the skip.
  - The skill write MUST happen only for Claude targets. When the only target is `codex` or `gemini`, init MUST NOT create `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` — even under `--with-skill`, which is silently ignored for non-Claude-only runs.
  - The CLAUDE.md stanza appended by init MUST include the `/tnl-feature` slash-command reference line ONLY when `--with-skill` is set AND Claude is a target. When `--with-skill` is not set, the stanza written for Claude MUST be identical to the Codex/Gemini stanza (no slash-command line), so the stanza never advertises a skill the adopter didn't install.
  - The end-of-run summary MUST include `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` in the `Created` or `Skipped (already present)` section only when `--with-skill` is set AND Claude is a target.
  - Tests MUST cover: default `--agent claude` (no `--with-skill`) writes NO `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` and the CLAUDE.md stanza does NOT contain `/tnl-feature`; `--agent claude --with-skill` writes `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` and the stanza DOES contain `/tnl-feature`; `.claude/commands/` directory auto-created under `--with-skill`; existing skill file under `--with-skill` → skipped and reported; skill NOT written when `--agent codex --with-skill` or `--agent gemini --with-skill` (skill is Claude-only); end-of-run summary includes the skill path under `Created` / `Skipped (already present)` only when `--with-skill` + Claude target; idempotency round-trips under both default and `--with-skill` runs; `TNL_FEATURE_SKILL_TEMPLATE` contains frontmatter `description:`, `$ARGUMENTS`, and a reference to `CLAUDE.md`; `TNL_FEATURE_SKILL_TEMPLATE` does NOT contain `## 3.` / `## 5.` / `## 7.` numbered-step markers that would duplicate the stanza flow.

non-goals:
  - Iterating on the `/tnl-feature` step text beyond the initial template — content tweaks over time are edits to this TNL, not new TNLs.
  - Installing or configuring the PreToolUse hook — next A6 TNL.
  - Packaging a Claude Code plugin — deferred to B4.
  - Publishing the skill to a registry or marketplace.
  - Skills for other agents (Codex, Gemini) — those surfaces don't expose slash commands in v1 scope.

rationale:
  Why embed the skill template as a string constant rather than bundle
  a separate template file: matches the existing `WORKFLOW_TEMPLATE`
  pattern in the same module. When the template count outgrows
  inline constants, we switch to a bundled `templates/` directory.

  Why tie skill installation to the Claude target only: agents without
  slash-command surfaces can't use the file. Installing it for them
  would be dead weight.

  Why CLAUDE.md must reference the skill when installed: the skill
  is user-invoked via `/tnl-feature`. Without a pointer in CLAUDE.md,
  agents and users won't discover it. The reference only appears when
  `--with-skill` is set so the stanza never advertises a command the
  adopter didn't install.

  Why skill is opt-in rather than default: after the skill body was
  collapsed to a thin pointer at CLAUDE.md's stanza, installing it
  by default only added a no-op middleman that some agents auto-invoke
  on every feature request, running the pointer rather than the stanza
  directly. The stanza fires the same task flow either way. Adopters
  who want an explicit `/tnl-feature` command pass `--with-skill`;
  everyone else gets a lighter install. Codex and Gemini skill support
  is deferred to follow-up TNLs (`codex-skill-register`,
  `gemini-skill-register`) — both agents support project-scoped skills
  via different file formats, so extending the mechanism deserves its
  own review.
